It is awesome how pedestrians and bicycles can sometimes share the space and find a way of all being equally safe. Pedestrians with their heavy backpacks extend the width enormously and make the space even more limited.

One should be very careful in Haiti, because most of the time, the drivers tend to be very lenient and rambunctious, and they aren’t ready to slow down or give way to pedestrians. So, my advice to the spectators from the rest of the world, is the observer of this collegial hazards and excellent harmonization of accurate dash space management in Haiti would

probably be able to predict those unusual turns in your otherwise planned or thought-about

surroundings.

I decided to practice the dashing on the bicycle in Haiti as I was in Barre de L’Isle at the first time. One of the first and most exciting stimulations which triggered the ‘I feel like I’m in a movie,’

feeling occurred when I was getting ready to cross the street. The Haitian Sign Language I learned in HCMC was now in action as I began speaking in this sign language to the pedestrians
